When writing or editing code and text, follow these rules to avoid AI-sounding patterns. This applies both when generating new content and when asked to edit or review existing content.

## Prevention: do not generate these patterns

### Prose

**Banned vocabulary** — never use these words or phrases:
tapestry, testament, delve, underscore, pivotal, comprehensive, multifaceted, evolving landscape, vibrant, crucial, moreover, furthermore, in conclusion, serves as a reminder, stands as a testament, ingrained, indelible, leveraging, seamlessly, robust, cutting-edge, revolutionary, innovative, groundbreaking, streamline, utilize (use "use"), facilitate (use a simpler verb), endeavor, commence (use "start"), subsequently (use "then"), it is worth noting, it is important to note, notably

**Structure**
- Sentence case for all headings. Not title case.
- No emojis as bullets or section markers.
- Straight quotes only (" '). No curly/smart quotes.
- One em dash per paragraph maximum.
- Bold only the one thing per section that must not be missed.

**Tone**
- Never open with "Great question!", "Absolutely!", "Certainly!", or "Happy to help".
- Never close with "I hope this helps!", "Let me know if you have questions", or any goodbye.
- No sycophantic affirmations before answering.
- No "As of my last update" or training-cutoff disclaimers in document output.

**Claims**
- Name experts by name and date, or do not invoke them.
- No "not just X, it's Y" constructions.
- No lists padded or truncated to exactly three items.
- One hedge per claim maximum ("could", "might", "often"). Make conditions explicit.
- No generic conclusions that apply to any topic.

**Filler** — never write these:
- "in order to" (use "to")
- "due to the fact that" (use "because")
- "it is worth noting that"
- "it is important to note that"
- "at the end of the day"
- "with that said"

### Code

**Comments**
- Never write a comment that restates what the code does at the same abstraction level.
- Never add section headers inside functions (# Setup, # Main logic, # Cleanup).
- Never write apology comments ("# Hacky but works", "# TODO: clean this up later").
- Comments explain why, not what. If why is obvious, write no comment.

**Naming**
- Never append type to variable names: not userDataObject, configurationSettings, errorMessageString, listOfUsers.
- Never use standalone generic names as a primary identifier: result, data, info, manager, handler, helper, util, service.
- Name the concept, not the container or lifecycle phase.

**Commit messages**
- Imperative mood, lowercase subject line.
- Never use: "various", "several", "enhance", "improve code quality", "update codebase".
- Name the specific thing changed and what was done to it.
- Body explains why, not what. Omit body if why is obvious.
- Never write past tense. Never write "in order to".

**Docstrings**
- Never open a docstring with "This function serves as..." or "This class represents...".
- Never write a docstring that only restates the signature.
- Describe behavior from the caller's perspective.

**Tests**
- Test names describe scenario and expected outcome: test_expired_token_returns_401, not test_auth.
- Never add # Arrange / # Act / # Assert section headers.

**Error messages**
- Name the cause, not the symptom: "user_id missing from session", not "an error occurred".
- Never write "An unexpected error occurred. Please try again later."

